# React Component Standards

## File Structure

- One component per file. The named export matches the filename: `PieceCard.tsx` exports `PieceCard`.
- Props interface is defined in the same file, not in a central types file (unless the interface is shared by 3+ components).
- Co-locate test files: `PieceCard.test.tsx` next to `PieceCard.tsx`.

## Size Limits

- No component file exceeds 200 lines. If a component grows beyond this, split it into subcomponents in the same directory.
- Complex components get their own subdirectory: `components/gallery/MockupViewer/index.tsx` with subcomponents alongside.

## Accessibility

- All `<Image>` and `<img>` elements have a descriptive `alt` attribute. Never use empty `alt=""` for content images (only for decorative images).
- All interactive elements (buttons, links, toggles) are keyboard-accessible.
- Use semantic HTML: `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<article>`, `<header>`, `<footer>`.
- Color contrast meets WCAG AA (4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text).

## Styling

- Use Tailwind CSS classes exclusively. No inline `style` attributes.
- Mobile-first responsive design: every component must render correctly at 320px viewport width.
- Use the project's design tokens (CSS custom properties) for colors, fonts, and spacing.

## Data Formatting

- Currency values use `Intl.NumberFormat` with explicit locale and currency:
  ```tsx
  new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { style: "currency", currency: "USD" }).format(price)
  ```
- Dates use `Intl.DateTimeFormat` or a lightweight formatter. No raw ISO strings in the UI.

## Patterns

- Avoid prop drilling beyond 2 levels. Use composition (children, render props) or context.
- Event handlers are named `onAction` in props (e.g., `onSelect`, `onClose`) and `handleAction` internally.
- Loading states use skeleton components, not spinners, for content-heavy pages.
